Section
Purpose
To enable safe and reliable transfer of crude oil between Escravos Terminal and tankers loading at the SBMs.
Attachments
Section
Scope

This document establishes guidelines for the transfer of crude oil between Escravos Terminal and tankers at the Escravos SBMs. It applies to Escravos Export Group, BOP personnel and vessels loading at this terminal to enable safe and reliable transfer of crude oil between Escravos Terminal and tankers loading at the SBMs.

Prerequisites / Requirements

This OP shall not conflict with standardized OE processes (such as MSRE Standardized OE Process) or any local or international regulatory requirements or any other process or requirements adopted by the BU. In the event of doubt the most stringent requirements shall apply.

Industry guidelines should also be referenced when preparing or reviewing operating procedures. In any event, all industry guidelines that fall within scope of the respective BU operations must also be complied with .

Operations Readiness Review
Section
Procedure Sequence
WARNING
﻿
  • Nothing in this SOP, or the exercise of authority of personnel in complying with this SOP, shall relieve a vessel master from carrying out independent responsibilities to provide safe crude oil transfer.
  •  Notwithstanding the above, all personnel shall be encouraged to exercise their Stop Work Authority in the event there is any uncertainty regarding safe operations, integrity or condition of cargo hoses and ancillaries, performance of personnel or doubt over the condition of tanker equipment.
Attachments
NOTE
﻿
  • Terminal Information Booklet and Crude Oil Berthing/Loading document shall be used in conjunction with this SOP to ensure that all information is readily available and that nothing is omitted in error
    		•
    Attachments
    Crude Oil Berthing Loading Doc. Term. Copy
    Attachments
    ADVISE BOP Supervisor of impending operations in a timely manner so that he may prepare his personnel and systems for the operation.
    Attachments
    Prepare the BOP pressure recorder for loading operations.
    Attachments
    Close both Gas Injection valves to SBM 3, if the vessel is to load at SBM 3.
    Attachments
    VERIFY  to MM1 that both Gas Injection valves to SBM 3 are Open, and shall remain Open , if the vessel is to load at SBM 2.
    Attachments
    Connect the cargo hoses and fully open the butterfly valves and lock in position.
    Attachments
    CONDUCT   Pre Transfer Conference, as described in SOP 3966, with Chief Officer and complete Ship/Shore Check List
    Attachments
    MM-Shore Checklist
    AGREE with Chief Officer on Loading Sequence and Topping off sequence
    Attachments

    Complete Vessel Line Up Check List.

     
    Attachments
    Vessel Line-Up Checklist
    Verify line up in CCR.
    Attachments

    Verify on Deck that tanker cross-over and drop-lines are properly lined up.

     
    Attachments
    VERIFY  to MM1 that Hose end Valves are opened and locked, Pressure recorder connected and running and Manifold Valves fully opened
    Attachments
    PACK the line when instructed to do so by MM1
    Attachments
    NOTIFY  MM1 when line is fully packed
    Attachments
    Open Escravos Incoming valve (MOV-820), and the export valve to the loading berth. (MOV-803 for SBM 2 or MOV-804 for SBM 3) when instructed to do so by MM1
    Attachments
    Instruct the Export Tanker CCR to line up properly and open the initial two tanks and the receiving Manifold valves.
    Attachments
    CARRY out the MM-Shore Check List with Tank Farm Ctrl Rm. , BOP Ctrl Rm and CCR
    Attachments
    MM-Shore Checklist
    CAUTION
    ﻿
    • No loading shall take place until the Mooring Master and Export Tanker Chief Officer have completed the pre-transfer conference and the checklists required by SOP-3966
    • Two Mooring Masters shall be present for the start of cargo. One at the vessel manifold and the other on the bridge, such that there is clear radio communication with Tank Farm Control Room and BOP Ctrl Rm
    Attachments

    Cargo Transfer at Offshore Berths shall be suspended if any of following Environmental Limits are exceeded:

     • Wind speed (Knots) – 35 kts

    • Wave Height (meters) – 4.0 mtrs

    • Current – 2.5 kts

    • Lightning in vicinity

    •Thunderstorm in vicinity

    The final decision to stop cargo transfer is dependent on varying criteria that the Mooring Master assesses, having due regard to the safety of life, property and environment at the terminal

    Attachments
    Attachments
    Commence  loading at shore minimum - a rate of approximately 11,000 barrels/hour (One Booster Pump and One Shipping Pump running), when instructed to do so by MM1. This rate shall be maintained until system integrity is verified.
    Attachments
    WARNING
    ﻿  At start-up and at all times during the transfer, the line pressure shall be monitored at Escravos Tank Farm control room, BOP and vessel’s manifold. The BOP shall also provide the Mooring Master and Escravos Tank Farm control room with the BOP in-coming and out-going pressures on request.
    Attachments
    VERIFY  to MM1 when flow at the manifold and confirm integrity of the hoses, manifold and Deck piping system
    Attachments
    VERIFY   to MM1 when receiving cargo in to designated tanks and confirm onboard piping systems integrity status.
    Attachments
    Open fully, sufficient cargo tanks (3 or more) to receive shore maximum rate when instructed to do so by MM1.
    Attachments

    Increase gradually to shore maximum. (Additional Shipping and Booster pumps are started and the rate increased to shore maximum of approximately 23,000 barrels/hour, governed by shore line and BOP pressures. Pressure at the BOP at maximum rate is maintained between 60 and 75 psi).

    Attachments
    Stop the loading if excessive or abnormal line pressure is observed in the Shore line and/or BOP, in accordance with SOP NMA-TER-0-25-OP-3311.
    Attachments
    WARNING
    ﻿

    If any non-urgent stoppages are required, loading shall be stopped in accordance with ‘Normal Stop’ procedure contained in SOP NMA- TER-0-25-OP-3311.

    Should cargo be stopped for any reason and any valves on the vessel or BOP are closed, all steps in this procedure shall be followed for resumption of loading operations as if it is a new operation.

    If any urgent stoppage is required from the vessel, loading shall be stopped in accordance with emergency stop procedure contained in SOP Export Communications During Cargo Transfers(and also SOP Tanker Pre-Transfer Conference)

    If any urgent stoppage is required from Escravos Tank Farm control room or BOP, loading shall be stopped in accordance with emergency stop procedure contained in SOP NMA-TER-0-25-OP-3311.
    Attachments
    Attachments
    VERIFY  throughout the loading that the items of the pre-transfer check list, the requirements of Escravos terminal regulations, the recommendations of ISGOTT and good seamanship and tanker practice are strictly followed.
    Attachments
    Make frequent checks of the export hose cam-locks to ensure the cams remain correctly engaged and secure.
    Attachments
    vERIFY  MM2 is  present in the vessel’s cargo control room before any critical change is made to the vessel’s cargo system line-up.
    Attachments
    Identify possible changes to vessel line up during loading and address in ‘Vessel Line-Up Checklist’ prior to commencement of loading operations.
    Attachments
    Vessel Line-Up Checklist
    Compare ship and shore cargo figures at hourly intervals, to ensure pipeline integrity and custody transfer systems integrity are maintained.
    Attachments
    Monitor the ship/shore difference and trend, and investigate any significant difference by all means available to reconcile the difference
    Attachments
    WARNING
    ﻿

     In determining what constitutes a significant difference, the Mooring Master shall consider, but not be limited to the following factors: Vessel’s Experience Factor; vessel list and trim and the corrections for same; vessel motion and sea condition; ship/shore clock synchronization; limitations of the vessel’s volume and temperature measurement systems; any assumed API and temperature; percentage of nomination loaded; vessel line(s) contents and whether inclusive or exclusive of ship’s figure.

    Where there is ambiguity, the clarification from the Senior Mooring Master (SMM) shall prevail

    The Mooring Master shall consider the ship/shore difference expressed as a percentage of the shore metered figure. A difference of 0.3% or more (with VEF applied) is significant.

    Attachments
    Stop the loading and inform the Senior Mooring Master should any significant difference not be reconciled.
    Attachments
    Resume Loading when ship/shore difference reconciliation is achieved.
    Attachments
    Maintain minimum positive I.G. pressure inside the tanks throughout loading
    Attachments
    Attachments
    Consult with both the vessel and Escravos Tank Farm control room to ensure that cargo completion procedures are clear with all parties, and re-confirm if completion of loading will be to Ship-Stop or Shore-Stop, at least one hour before the estimated time of completion.
    Attachments
    Alert the second Mooring Master to be present in the vessel cargo control room at the final stage of the operation
    Attachments
    Give Tank Farm Control Room 30 minutes notice to reduce the loading rate to not more than 20,000 barrels/hour when there is 20,000 barrels to go to completion of the nominated volume.
    Attachments
    Notify Tank Farm Control Room to reduce the loading rate to approximately 11,000 barrels/hour at least 15 minutes before loading into two tanks only (One Booster Pump and One Shipping Pump running), at least 15 minutes before loading to 2 tanks only, should the vessel require loading into two cargo tanks only either toward completion of loading or at any time during loading.
    Attachments
    Notify the Tanker CCR when there is 20,000 barrels to go to completion of the nominated volume and a countdown of 10000, 5000, 4000, 3000, 2000, 1000, if loading is to be completed by SHORE Stop.
    Attachments
    Give a half an hour notice to the Tank Farm Control when it will remain 20,000 barrels to go to completion of the required volume and a countdown of 10000, 5000, 4000, 3000, 2000, 1000 if loading is to be completed by SHIP Stop.
    Attachments
    NOTIFY  MM1 when loading completed and communicate Time of Completion
    Attachments
    VERIFY  that on completion, hose end valve(s), manifold valve(s) and one tank valve is kept opened unless instructed otherwise by MM1
    Attachments
    NOTIFY  MM1 when Export V/V fully closed and zero pressure in the line
    Attachments
    Close Escravos Incoming V/V (MOV-820) and inform MM1 when fully shut
    Attachments
    Close the export valve to the loading berth (MOV-803 for SBM 2 or MOV-804 for SBM 3) and inform MM1 when fully shut
    Attachments
    Close Manifold V/V and start draining manifold when instructed to do so by MM1
    Attachments
    NOTIFY  MM2 when manifold fully drained
    Attachments
    Close and lock hose end v/v.
    Attachments
    Open Gas injection Valve to berth SBM 3 if loaded to SBM3 and inform MM1
    Attachments
    NOTE
    ﻿ Hose disconnection shall take place under the Mooring Masters direction in accordance with SOP Connection/disconnection and Handling of Cargo Transfer Hoses at Offshore Berths

    Consequence of Deviation

    Condition

    Safe Operating Range

    Consequence of Deviation

    System Response

    Steps to Recover

    Tanker Equipment failure

    Fully Operational

    Environmental Pollution, Injury, Fatality, Damage to Infrastructure, Loss of Revenue

    Stop loading

    Un-berth, Await improvement in conditions, Re-berth and resume loading

    Environmental Conditions unfavourable

    Within Tolerances

    Environmental Pollution, Injury, Fatality, Damage to Infrastructure, Loss of Revenue

    Stop loading

    Un-berth, Await improvement in conditions, Re-berth and resume loading

    Failure Of Tug or Towing Boat

    Fully Operational

    Environmental Pollution, Injury, Fatality, Damage to Infrastructure, Loss of Revenue

    Stop loading

    Get engines ready, replace tow tug with SBY. Resume loading

    Continual Improvement

    Continual improvement to this document is ensured by means of periodic reviews and training by Supervisors, OJL Specialists and other processes. Such processes include formal and informal audits, Operating Procedure drills, unit tailgate forums, ORD feedbacks, incident investigations reports and updates from facility changes or upgrades.

    • Latest versions of the hardcopy document shall be used to carry out the task and each step shall be duly initialed upon completion.  Users of this procedure must follow every step as required and ensure that the steps provided were correct and adequate.
    • If changes to this Operating Procedure are identified during use, mark up the hardcopy with a red pen, return it to your Supervisor for review and approval prior to initiating a change request for updating this document within SmartProcedures.
    • The On-the-job (OJL) specialist shall train all users about new updates to this document
    Attachments
    Section
    Roles and Responsibilities
    • Monitors and provides functional supervision of all cargo transfer activities that may impact safe operations 
    • Supervises all cargo transfer activities, providing continuous overview to identify and stop potentially unsafe acts or unsafe conditions that could lead to injury or fatality or damage to equipment.
    • Ensures that all environmental, operational and equipment limitations are not being exceeded during cargo transfer.
    • Conducts pre-transfer checklists and conference with Tank Farm Ctrl, BOP and Chief Officer.
    • Supervise terminal riggers (OMSOs).
    • Provide guidance and advice to tanker officers and crew during cargo transfer activities, ensuring safe practices and compliance with terminal requirements.
    • Ensure that all cargo transfer activities are carried out in compliance with the marine terminal operating procedures and BU procedures and requirements.
    • Provides equipment inspection report to the ASMM responsible for maintenance and give clear advice if equipment replacement is needed.
    • Ensures all required documentation is prepared 
    • Keeps watch on the bridge during cargo transfer
    • MM2 Assists MM1 in overall supervision
    • Supervises CCR activities during any alterations in loading sequences and during start up and topping off operation
    Attachments

    Keeps Watch at the Manifold and on the Bow

    Reports to the Mooring Master if there is any doubt with respect to the condition or integrity of any equipment.

    Monitors pressure recorder, if any pressure observed reports to MM on Watch

    Monitors position and integrity of transfer hoses and manifold connections,at the tanker manifold

    Attachments
    • Ensures tanker and crew safety and security throughout operation
    • Complies with all Terminal Regs
    • Completes all required documentation on completion of Loading/Discharging
    Attachments
    • Supervises loading/discharging on board tanker
    • Carries out loading/discharging as per plan 
    • Complies with all Terminal regulations
    • Completes all required documentation on completion
    • Ensures CCR is always manned with qualified OOW
    • Ensures all watchkeeping Officers are familiar with loading/disch. and deballasting as per plane
    • Ensures vsl’s stability
    • Ensures Watch is kept on the Bow and at the Manifold throughout of operation

    Communication Protocol
    NOTE
    ﻿ Two Way communications must be tested and established on VHF Channel 10A(Primary) and 10(Secondary) between the OSV,BOP and Tank farm Control before the commencement of the operation
